{
  "family": "Favorskii and Homo-Favorskii Rearrangement",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "CC(C)C(=O)C(C)Cl"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "CC(C)C(C)C(=O)O"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "[OH-]"
    ],
    "rationale": "This is a classic textbook example of the Favorskii rearrangement. It features a simple, acyclic alpha-halo ketone (2-chloro-3-methyl-2-butanone) that rearranges in the presence of a base to form a carboxylic acid (2,3-dimethylbutanoic acid). The mechanism proceeds through a cyclopropanone intermediate, which is characteristic of this reaction. The chosen substrate is simple, avoids rings in the starting material, and clearly demonstrates the skeletal rearrangement from a ketone to a carboxylic acid derivative.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses a simple acyclic alpha-halo ketone and a basic reagent. It avoids aromatic rings, complex functional groups, or ring expansion motifs that could be confused with other named reactions like the Ramberg-Bäcklund rearrangement (which involves a sulfone) or various ring expansion reactions (like Tiffeneau-Demjanov). The product is a simple carboxylic acid, avoiding esters or amides which might broaden the search space unnecessarily."
  }
}
